{"id":"1512.01430","submitter":"P. J. Mart\\'inez","authors":"Pedro J. Mart\\'inez and Ricardo Chac\\'on","title":"Impulse-Induced Optimum Signal Amplification in Scale-Free Networks","comments":"arXiv admin note: text overlap with arXiv:1412.3583","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevE.93.042311","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.soc-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Optimizing information transmission across a network is an essential task for\ncontrolling and manipulating generic information-processing systems. Here, we\nshow how topological amplification effects in scale-free networks of signaling\ndevices are optimally enhanced when the $\\it{impulse}$ transmitted by periodic\nexternal signals (time integral over two consecutive zeros) is maximum. This is\ndemonstrated theoretically by means of a star-like network of overdamped\nbistable systems subjected to $\\it{generic}$ zero-mean periodic signals, and\nconfirmed numerically by simulations of scale-free networks of such systems.\nOur results show that the enhancer effect of increasing values of the signal's\nimpulse is due to a correlative increase of the energy transmitted by the\nperiodic signals, while it is found to be resonant-like with respect to the\ntopology-induced amplification mechanism.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 17 Nov 2015 15:16:34 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-05-04"}
